1
00:00:00,219 --> 00:00:02,039
Previously on <i>Longmire</i>

2
00:00:02,159 --> 00:00:03,114
Ignore the polls.

3
00:00:03,662 --> 00:00:06,382
I do. But there are some things
I cann't ignore.

4
00:00:06,502 --> 00:00:08,553
You know what would help?
Dirt.

5
00:00:08,673 --> 00:00:12,127
You got any juicy Longmire secrets,
now would be the time to spill 'em.

6
00:00:12,247 --> 00:00:13,991
Where did you get those eyes?

7
00:00:14,111 --> 00:00:17,824
My dad and my ex-boyfriend are in
the middle of a nasty campaign fight.

8
00:00:17,944 --> 00:00:20,258
- And recently I found out that my mother...
- Your mother what?

9
00:00:20,378 --> 00:00:22,977
- I know what happened in Denver.
- No you don't.

10
00:00:23,097 --> 00:00:25,850
Word of your wifes' murder
won't leave this room.

11
00:00:25,970 --> 00:00:29,789
But I think that right now your daughter
might need you more than the county does.

12
00:00:31,861 --> 00:00:33,061
Walt: Your family's
been coming here

13
00:00:33,162 --> 00:00:34,796
every summer since the '80s,
right?

14
00:00:34,864 --> 00:00:36,598
Woman: The '70s, actually.
And we're here year-round now,

15
00:00:36,699 --> 00:00:38,433
so I can finally vote for you.

16
00:00:38,501 --> 00:00:40,068
We just got to get out
that vote!

17
00:00:40,136 --> 00:00:43,004
May I borrow the sheriff
for just a moment?

18
00:00:43,105 --> 00:00:44,506
Uh, what for?

19
00:00:44,607 --> 00:00:46,441
I think she's asking you
to dance.

20
00:00:46,509 --> 00:00:48,076
I'm not sure that's such a...
such a...

21
00:00:48,144 --> 00:00:50,245
Go on.
Come on!

22
00:00:50,346 --> 00:00:54,049
[ Music ]

23
00:01:06,262 --> 00:01:07,862
Woman:
All right, sheriff!

24
00:01:07,964 --> 00:01:09,664
[ Cheers and applause ]

25
00:01:09,765 --> 00:01:12,367
Man: Nice one, Walt.

26
00:01:12,435 --> 00:01:13,635
[ Laughs ]

27
00:01:13,703 --> 00:01:15,637
Hung me out to dry there.

28
00:01:15,705 --> 00:01:18,139
Price of politics.
[ Laughs ]

29
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:20,342
You, uh, want to dance?

30
00:01:20,443 --> 00:01:23,278
Two vodka tonics, ma'am.

31
00:01:23,346 --> 00:01:25,246
Thank you.

32
00:01:28,250 --> 00:01:29,851
Ruby.

33
00:01:29,952 --> 00:01:31,219
Ooh, thank you.
Mm-hmm.

34
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:33,388
I thought maybe you got lost.

35
00:01:33,489 --> 00:01:35,023
That block of ice was charming,

36
00:01:35,124 --> 00:01:36,491
but it's not a very efficient
way to make a drink.

37
00:01:36,592 --> 00:01:37,492
[ Chuckles ]

38
00:01:37,593 --> 00:01:38,893
Look at Ferg.

39
00:01:38,995 --> 00:01:41,296
Ooh, light on his feet.

40
00:01:41,397 --> 00:01:43,298
Woman: You go, boy!

41
00:01:43,399 --> 00:01:45,300
[ Cheering ]

42
00:01:47,970 --> 00:01:51,506
[ Cheers and applause ]

43
00:02:03,619 --> 00:02:06,788
[ Music ]

44
00:02:09,358 --> 00:02:12,694
[ Cheers and applause ]

45
00:02:12,795 --> 00:02:15,330
[ Glass dings ]

46
00:02:15,431 --> 00:02:19,668
I have been asked to say a few
words about tomorrow's election.

47
00:02:19,769 --> 00:02:24,072
We have all grown accustomed to
the modern drumbeat for change.

48
00:02:24,173 --> 00:02:27,342
Our opponent seems particularly
fond of the word.

49
00:02:27,410 --> 00:02:30,578
And while I believe
that change can be good,

50
00:02:30,680 --> 00:02:34,182
I do think people too often
underestimate the value

51
00:02:34,283 --> 00:02:36,117
of things that never change.

52
00:02:36,185 --> 00:02:38,687
[ Cheers and applause ]

53
00:02:38,788 --> 00:02:42,957
My friend Walt
is one of those things.

54
00:02:43,059 --> 00:02:46,361
[ Cheers and applause ]

55
00:02:46,462 --> 00:02:49,264
Who would ask him to change
his loyalty,

56
00:02:49,365 --> 00:02:51,533
his honesty,

57
00:02:51,634 --> 00:02:53,935
his intelligence,
and compassion?

58
00:02:54,003 --> 00:02:55,870
Not me.

59
00:02:55,971 --> 00:02:57,305
Though some of us <i>do</i> think

60
00:02:57,373 --> 00:02:58,973
that maybe it is time
he got a cellphone.

61
00:02:59,075 --> 00:03:00,075
[ Laughter ]

62
00:03:00,176 --> 00:03:04,245
But other than that, sheriff.

63
00:03:04,346 --> 00:03:05,313
Speech!

64
00:03:05,414 --> 00:03:08,283
Speech!

65
00:03:08,350 --> 00:03:12,654
[ All chanting "Walt!" ]

66
00:03:20,996 --> 00:03:23,098
Man: Thataboy, Walt!

67
00:03:24,834 --> 00:03:25,767
Uh...
[ Feedback ]

68
00:03:25,835 --> 00:03:27,268
Okay?

69
00:03:27,369 --> 00:03:28,503
[ Laughter ]

70
00:03:28,604 --> 00:03:32,540
Uh...

71
00:03:36,078 --> 00:03:38,646
Thanks.

72
00:03:38,748 --> 00:03:41,449
[ Cheers and applause ]

73
00:03:46,922 --> 00:03:48,556
[ All chanting "Walt!" ]

74
00:03:52,094 --> 00:03:55,997
Walt, come on.
That's not necessary.

75
00:03:56,098 --> 00:03:58,299
I'll get that in the morning.

76
00:03:58,367 --> 00:04:01,503
Doesn't seem right to leave you
with a mess.

77
00:04:01,570 --> 00:04:05,273
Who said anything
about you leaving?

78
00:04:05,374 --> 00:04:07,108
Hmm?

79
00:04:27,730 --> 00:04:29,864
I'm sorry. I...

80
00:04:29,932 --> 00:04:32,367
I got a big day.

81
00:04:32,468 --> 00:04:34,302
Yeah, got to get your rest.

82
00:04:34,403 --> 00:04:36,237
Right.

83
00:04:36,305 --> 00:04:38,640
I, uh... yeah.

84
00:04:46,115 --> 00:04:47,649
[ Crickets chirping ]

85
00:04:55,658 --> 00:04:57,025
[ Door opens ]

86
00:05:02,031 --> 00:05:05,500
[ Clatter ]

87
